The rand has had a tumultuous 2022 so far, weakening sharply in late April, strengthening in mid-June only to weaken once again in recent sessions. Bianca Botes, director at Citadel Global said that there are four major factors contributing to this, namely; the global environment spurred on by geopolitical events such as the Russia-Ukraine war, the risk of recession, investors looking for safe havens, and people flocking to the dollar. The rand hit its weakest point against the dollar at the start of July, captured at R16.84 amid fears of a looming global recession. According to Reuters, South African analysts have cautioned that the rand is not out of the woods yet, noting that the country still faces risk factors that could further weaken the currency. In afternoon trade on Thursday (7 July), the rand traded at the following levels against the major currencies: Dollar/Rand: R16.75
Pound/Rand:R20.09
